V{{Distinguish2|the French diplomat and scholar [[Jean Nicot]]}}\u000a\u000a'''Jean George Pierre Nicod''' (1893, France &ndash; 16 February 1924, [[Geneva]], Switzerland) was a French [[philosopher]] and [[logician]].\u000a\u000a==Biography==\u000aIn his best known work, he showed that the classical [[propositional calculus]] could be derived from one axiom and one rule, both expressed using the [[Sheffer stroke]]. He also proposed the [[Nicod's axiom]] and developed [[Nicod's criterion]].\u000a\u000aNicod died at the age of 31 from [[tuberculosis]].\u000a\u000aSee also [[Carl Hempel]]'s [[raven paradox]].\u000a\u000a== Legacy ==\u000aThe [[Institut Jean Nicod]] (Paris) &mdash; a branch of the French ''Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique'' ([[CNRS]]) -- is research laboratory at the interface between [[philosophy]], [[cognitive science]], and the [[social science]]s &mdash; was named in honour of Nicod's memory. Jean Nicod's name is also commemorated by the prestigious [[Jean Nicod Prize|Jean Nicod Lectures]], delivered annually in Paris by a leading [[philosopher of mind]] or philosophically oriented [[cognitive scientist]], and published as a series by the [[MIT Press]]. The lecturer is awarded the [[Jean Nicod Prize]] by the [[CNRS]].\u000a\u000a== Main works ==\u000a*1917, "A Reduction in the Number of Primitive Propositions of Logic", ''Proc. Camb. Phil. Soc.'' '''19''': 32-41.\u000a*1921, "La géométrie des sensations de mouvement", ''Revue de métaphysique et de morale'' '''28''': 537-43.\u000a*1922, "Les tendances philosophiques de M. Bertrand Russell", ''Revue de métaphysique et de morale'' '''29''': 77-84.\u000a*1922, "Mathematical Logic and the Foundations of Mathematics" in ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]'': ''The New Volumes, vol. 3'', 12th ed. 874-76.\u000a*1923. ''La géométrie dans le monde sensible''. Thèse, Univ. de Paris.\u000a*1923. ''Le problème logique de l'induction''. Thèse complémentaire, Univ. de Paris.\u000a*1924. "Les relations des valeurs et les relations de sens en logique formelle", ''Revue de métaphysique et de morale'' '''31''': 467-80.\u000a* 1924, "Freedom of Association and Trade Unionism: An Introductory Survey", ''International Labor Review'' '''9''': 467-80.\u000a*1930. ''Foundations of Geometry & Induction, Containing Geometry in a Sensible World and the Logical Problem of Induction'', with prefaces by [[Bertrand Russell]] and [[André Lalande (philosopher)|André Lalande]]. London: Kegan Paul, Trench, Trubner & Co. New York: Harcourt, Brace & Co.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Dresden, Arnold|authorlink=Arnold Dresden|title=Review: ''Foundations of Geometry and Induction'' by Jean Nicod|journal=Bull. Amer. Math. Soc.|year=1931|volume=37|issue=3|pages=152\u2013153|doi=10.1090/S0002-9904-1931-05111-9}}</ref> Reprinted 2000, London: Routledge.\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a{{wikisource author}}\u000a* [http://institutnicod.ens.fr/jn.htm Jean Nicod (1893-1924): Biographical note and works] (in French)\u000a* [http://www.institutnicod.org/ Institut Jean Nicod (CNRS)]\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Nicod, Jean}}\u000a[[Category:1893 births]]\u000a[[Category:1924 deaths]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century deaths from tuberculosis]]\u000a[[Category:French philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Logicians]]\u000a[[Category:French logicians]]\u000a[[Category:French male writers]]\u000a\u000a\u000a{{france-philosopher-stub}}
